            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the ephod",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] This garment (described ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 28:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 39:2-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") was made of fine twined linen with blue purple and scarlet threads, and fine gold wire. Its exact shape cannot be determined. There were two shoulder straps, on each of which was an engraved onyx stone, and a band made of the same material as the ephod and woven with it in one piece, which served to gird the ephod over the other garments. This band is called ‘the cunningly woven band’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the curious girdle",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " A.V.) of the ephod; the Heb. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥçshĕb",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " denotes textile work of the highest grade, employed only for the curtains of the Dwelling, the veil, the ephod, and the pouch for the Urim and Thummim. See note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 26:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where terms used for the different kinds of woven work are distinguished. The words ‘cunning,’ ‘cunningly’ were in Old English used to denote what is now termed ‘skilful,’ ‘skilfully.’ If the ephod consisted of front and back pieces, then the whole garment with its band would form a kind of waistcoat; if it consisted of a front piece only, it would resemble an apron. See Driver on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 28:5-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
