  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 7-9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The robing. The various articles of the priestly dress had been appointed and described before (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 28, 29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In these verses we see the order in which they were ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "put on",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". After the priests had, no doubt, changed their linen drawers, there came, first, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the coat",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, a close-fitting tunic of white linen, made with sleeves and covering the whole body; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "next the girdle",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the tunic, that is, a linen sash for tying the tunic round the body, with variegated ends hanging on each side to the ankles; thirdly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the robe",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, a blue vesture, woven of one piece, with holes for the head and arms to pass through, reaching from the neck to below the knee, the bottom being ornamented with blue, purple, and scarlet pomegranates, alternating with golden bells; fourthly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the ephod",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which consisted of two shoulder-pieces, or epaulettes, made of variegated linen and gold thread, fastened together in front and at the back by a narrow strap or band, from which hung, before and behind the wearer, two pieces of cloth confined below by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the curious girdle of the ephod",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, by a sash made of the same material as the ephod itself. Into the ephod were sewn two onyxes, one on each shoulder, in gold filigree settings, one of them engraven with the names of half of the tribes, and the other with the remaining half; and from two rosettes or buttons by the side of these stones depended twisted gold chains for the support of the breastplate. Fifth came ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the breastplate",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which was a square pocket, made of embroidered linen, a span long and a span broad, worn upon the breast and hanging from the gold chains above mentioned, the lower ends of the gold chain being tied to two rings at the upper and outer corner of the breastplate, while the upper and inner corner of the same was attached to the ephod by blue thread running through two sets of rings in the breastplate and ephod respectively. The outer side of the breastplate was stiffened and adorned by twelve precious stones, set in four rows of three, each stone having on it the name of one of the tribes of Israel. The breastplate being double and the two sides and the bottom being sewn up, the pocket formed by it had its opening at the top. Into this pocket were placed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the Urim and the Thummim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which were probably two balls of different colours, one of which on being drawn out indicated the approval of God, and the other his disapproval, as to any point on which the high priest consulted him. (The Jewish tradition, that the Divine answer by the Urim and the Thummim came by a supernatural light thrown on certain letters in the names of the tribes, has no foundation.) The last part of the dress to be put on was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the mitre",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or head-dress of linen, probably of the nature of a turban; to which, by a blue string, was attached ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the golden plate",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in such a way that it rested lengthwise on the forehead, and on this plate or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "holy crown",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " were inscribed the words,\" Holiness to the Lord.\" The investiture took place ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "as the Lord commanded Moses",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, in accordance with the instructions given in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Its purpose and its meaning in the eyes of the people would have been twofold: first, after the manner of the king's crown and the judge's robe, it served to manifest the fact that the function of priest was committed to the wearer; and next, it symbolized the necessity of being clothed upon with the righteousness of God, in order to be able to act as interpreter and mediator between God and man, thus foreshadowing the Divine Nature of him who should be the Mediator in antitype. Leviticus 8:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
